Next we demonstrate that magnetic impurities on the surface of a TI will rapidly destroy the topological protected bands.
To this end, we set $V_n=0$, $\tau_{n}=0$ and  $\Delta_1=\Delta_2=0$  in our model Hamiltonian, and 
consider a random Zeeman term $H^Z$ only, where $g^+=1$ and $g^-=0$ without loss of generality. 
Here the gap in the surface state band structure is induced by a finite mean value $b = \langle B^Z_z \rangle$. Figure~\ref{fig9} illustrates the radical spectral weight (DOS) transfer into the bulk gap when  magnetic surface disorder is present. In addition two notches in the DOS appear at $\omega\simeq \pm 2.5$ (the DOS even vanishes at these points for magnetic bulk disorder with $1.9<\beta<2.8$; for still larger $\beta$ Anderson disorder sets in). Note that already for a rather moderate disorder strength ($\beta=2$) the midband gap closes and the photoemission spectrum becomes completely incoherent.  
